[2] Nigeria: new case
Date: 2 Sep 2014
Source: Nigerian Eye [abridged, edited]
http://www.nigerianeye.com/2014/09/ebola-update-another-ebola-case-in-port.html


One of 3 people taken to the Ebola virus quarantine centre in Oduoha, Emohua Local Government Area of Rivers State, has tested positive for the disease. The latest case, an elderly woman, contracted the virus in Good Heart Hospital, the health facility where the doctor who treated a Nigerian ECOWAS diplomat [contact of index case Sawyer from Liberia] died last week. The 2 others -- a doctor and a pharmacist -- tested negative. Even though they had been released from the centre, another round of tests will be carried out to reconfirm their status. ...

Amidst fear of the Ebola virus disease (EVD) spreading in Nigeria, the federal government is increasing its capacity to curtail the spread of the virus, the health minister said on Mon [1 Sep 2014].

The minister of health, Onyebuchi Chukwu, revealed on Monday [1 Sep 2014] during the 2nd emergency National Council on Health meeting on the EVD outbreak in Nigeria, which was held in Abuja, that the federal ministry of health has steadily been increasing capacity to diagnose EVD.

Mr Chukwu said the virus can now be diagnosed at the following locations: NCDC Laboratory, Asokoro, Abuja; NCDC Laboratory at LUTH, Lagos; NCDC Laboratory at University College Hospital, Ibadan; Irrua Specialist Teaching Hospital Irrua, Edo State; Virology Laboratory of Redeemers University, Ogun State; the Irrua-based mobile laboratory, which has now been relocated from Enugu to Port Harcourt.

He stated that plans were at an advanced stage to enable the following laboratories: NCDC Laboratory at Aminu Kano Teaching Hospital, Kano; NCDC Laboratory at UPTH, Port Harcourt, while the federal ministry of health plans to procure additional mobile laboratories to be based in the following locations: Abakaliki, Port Harcourt, Bauchi, Jos and Sokoto. ...

The minister further revealed that Nigeria has indicated interest to participate in the clinical trials for Ebola virus disease vaccines, adding that the country has also applied for experimental drugs such as TKM-Ebola: "The Treatment Research Group (TRG) has been working hard to identify experimental drugs like Zmapp and also to make recommendations to government on further research on these drugs as well as vaccines for EVD treatment and prevention. Following the TRG's recommendation and in consultation with NAFDAC and NHREC, Nigeria has indicated interest to participate in the clinical trials for 2 candidate EVD vaccines and is considering a 3rd that may be added to the list. We have also applied for experimental drugs such as TKM-Ebola.

"The TRG has submitted a detailed profile and brief on the oral antiviral agent which the Japanese Government has offered to make available to affected countries through the WHO. We are now considering the profile and brief to enable us to reach a final decision on making it available to our patients."
http://allafrica.com/stories/201409020954.html?aa_source=slideout

